            <ITEM fqid="242263" is_admin_question="0" is_focus_question="0" is_info_only="0" qid="1937" question_code="007h" question_type="True/False" typeid="1">
                <QUESTION><![CDATA[Was this a Comprehensive PM?]]></QUESTION>
                <POLICY><![CDATA[Comprehensive PM vs Operational PMs (NOTE: ?Comprehensive PM? and ?Operational PM? are internal TSO terms and not to be used with the customers. The only term used with the customer and the only term appearing on customer reports will be ?PM?. For the fields ?Work performed on the equipment at the 3 comp sink, mop sink, etc?, the pick ?3-comp, mop sink, etc PM completed? applies to both Comprehensive and Operational PMs.)1. For Total Kitchen customers, complete the entire MWW PM part of the checklist on every PM. For the PGP non-MWW equipment in Total Kitchen locations, a Comprehensive PM will be performed once a year and the other PM visits during the year will get an Operational PM. 2. For customers receiving one annual PM or RE PM, (restaurants, C-stores, etc), a Comprehensive PM will be required on the one annual visit. 3. For non-MWW customers receiving more than one PM annually, only one of the PMs will be a Comprehensive PM and the others will be Operational PMs. (See the Service Entitlements Workbook on Box.net) Comprehensive PM Requirements: Check and test all component parts (inside and outside) of the dilution center, wall pumps, or dispensers to make sure they are functioning properly. Check all sanitizer levels and make sure all products are being diluted properly. Check for proper mounting. Visually inspect that correct mating caps or foot valve assembly parts are in place and in good condition. Replace any rusting screws. Clean all PGP equipment inside and out.  Make any installation adjustments needed or detail why they could not be done. Check the condition of racks and that they are securely attached. All product supply wall racks must be mounted below eye level. Preferably, racks should not be mounted below the water supply or the dilution center. FSTs should be knowledgeable of their assigned customers? preferences for mounting racks above or below the 3-comp sink. Fill spray bottles if low or empty. The Comprehensive PM includes annual replacement of the following parts regardless of condition: Metering tips/ULDs (refer to metering tip charts) and inlet water strainers. On the checklist, select all items from the list that apply. MWW squeeze tubes must be replaced every 6 months regardless of condition.Operational PM Requirements:  Operational PMs of the non-MWW PGP equipment includes testing and repairing the equipment as needed to ensure proper operation and dilution. Testing all sanitizer levels will be part of each Operational PM. It also includes cleaning the equipment on every visit. If needed, the tech will replace stickers, wall charts, and any parts required to keep the equipment operational.]]></POLICY>
                <QUESTION_TAGS/>
            </ITEM>
            <ITEM fqid="242265" is_admin_question="0" is_focus_question="0" is_info_only="0" qid="1404" question_code="068" question_type="True/False" typeid="1">
                <QUESTION><![CDATA[Was the Spare Parts Kit (SPK) available/stocked?]]></QUESTION>
                <POLICY><![CDATA[Not all customers use spare parts kits. FSTs should be knowledgeable of the requirements for all assigned customers. For new installations, check the template or install guidance to see if SPKs are included. If used, Spare parts kit (SPK) or phone-fix kit should be placed inside the Cleaning Guide Manual or zip-tied to binder rack if available. on PMs/RWs verify that the kit insert is available and current, if used. Ensure that the kit is complete with the correct parts. Replace missing/wrong parts in SPK. If you cannot find the SPK, ask the PIC to locate it. If selecting 'No', use as many Suggested Comments as may apply.]]></POLICY>
                <QUESTION_TAGS/>
            </ITEM>
